PUH-BrianMartell The golden ratio φ = (1 + √5)/2 ≈ 1.618 emerges directly from projections of the E₈ lattice root system into lower dimensions. E₈ has 240 roots — unit vectors in 8D. When projected onto a 2D Coxeter plane (optimal for visualizing symmetries), the roots form concentric rings with specific angular spacings tied to the lattice’s exceptional symmetry. These projections reveal icosahedral/pentagonal subgroups (5-fold rotation). The angles are multiples of 72° (360°/5), and the cosine of 36°/72° satisfies equations whose solutions are φ-related. Simple derivation: •  cos(2π/5) = cos(72°) = (√5 - 1)/4 = (φ - 1)/2. •  The characteristic polynomial for 5-fold rotation matrix eigenvalues includes φ as root. In PUH: This φ is the natural scaling factor between projected root shells — the lattice’s preferred “growth ratio” for hierarchical packing without periodicity (links to quasicrystals too). φ is baked into E₈’s exceptional geometry
